|}

{{BookCat}}

[[File:Ulysses, 1922.djvu|thumb|600px|center|page=587]]
<br>
==Annotations==
'''''alias'''''{{spaces|5}}''otherwise known as''. Although the phrase has been borrowed from Latin, it has become a naturalized English expression and is not generally italicized;<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=alias&allowed_in_frame=0 Online Etymology Dictionary.]</ref> but the narrator of this episode (Bloom?) italicizes most words that have been borrowed from foreign languages, whether they have been naturalized or not. See also [[Annotations_to_James_Joyce's_Ulysses/Cyclops/308|308.27]].


==References==
{{reflist}}


{|style="width: 23%; margin: 0px auto;" class="noprint"
|style="background-color: #efe; border: 1px solid SteelBlue; padding: 0.5em; font-size: small; text-align: center;"|'''[[Annotations to James Joyce's Ulysses]]'''<br />[[Annotations to James Joyce's Ulysses/Eumaeus/583|Preceding Page]] | [[Annotations to James Joyce's Ulysses/Page Index|Page Index]] | [[Annotations to James Joyce's Ulysses/Eumaeus/585|Next Page]]
|}

{{BookCat}}

[[File:Ulysses, 1922.djvu|thumb|600px|center|page=588]]
<br>
==Annotations==
'''''minutiae'''''{{spaces|5}}''minor details''; ''trifles''. Like ''alias'' on the previous page, ''[[wikt:minutia|minutiae]]'' is a late borrowing from Latin, which has become a naturalized English expression and is not generally italicized;<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=minutiae&allowed_in_frame=0 Online Etymology Dictionary.]</ref> but the narrator of this episode (Bloom?) italicizes every word that has been borrowed from a foreign language, whether naturalized or not.

