:''Note: The tengwar used in this article may not display properly unless [http://home.student.uu.se/j/jowi4905/fonts/annatar.html tengwar fonts] are installed.''

Tengwar is the script used to write Quenya. Though the chapters of this wikibook use a Latin transliteration for the sake of simplicity, Quenya is properly written using the Tengwar. For more information on Tengwar itself, see [[History of Elven Writing Systems]] and the [[w:Tengwar|Wikipedia article]] on the topic.

Tengwar is said to have different "modes", each of which determines what sound is assigned to each symbol. This article only covers the Quenya mode, which cannot be used to write non-elven words (your name, for example) as it lacks necessary sounds. English modes for Tengwar exist, though they are not standardized.

==Consonants==
Words are written from left to right, as in English.

{| class="wikitable"
!
!colspan="2"| A
!colspan="2"| B
!colspan="2"| C
!colspan="2"| D
|-
|1 || {{Tengwar|1}} || {{IPA|/t/}} || {{Tengwar|q}} || {{IPA|/p/}} || {{Tengwar|a}} || {{IPA|/k/}} || {{Tengwar|z}} || {{IPA|/kʷ/}}
|-
|2 || {{Tengwar|2}} || {{IPA|/nd/}} || {{Tengwar|w}} || {{IPA|/mb/}} || {{Tengwar|s}} || {{IPA|/ŋɡ/}} || {{Tengwar|x}} || {{IPA|/ŋɡʷ/}}
|-
|3 || {{Tengwar|3}} || {{IPA|/θ, s/}} || {{Tengwar|e}} || {{IPA|/f/}} || {{Tengwar|d}} || {{IPA|/x/}} || {{Tengwar|c}} || {{IPA|/ɣʷ/}}
|-
|4 || {{Tengwar|4}} || {{IPA|/nt/}} || {{Tengwar|r}} || {{IPA|/mp/}} || {{Tengwar|f}} || {{IPA|/ŋk/}} || {{Tengwar|v}} || {{IPA|/ŋkʷ/}}
|-
|5 || {{Tengwar|5}} || {{IPA|/n/}} || {{Tengwar|t}} || {{IPA|/m/}} || {{Tengwar|g}} || {{IPA|/ŋ/}} || {{Tengwar|b}} || {{IPA|/ŋʷ/}}
|-
|6 || {{Tengwar|6}} || {{IPA|/r/}} || {{Tengwar|y}} || {{IPA|/v/}} || {{Tengwar|h}} || {{IPA|/j/}} || {{Tengwar|n}} || {{IPA|/w, v/}}
|-
|7 || {{Tengwar|7}} || {{IPA|/r/}} || {{Tengwar|u}} || {{IPA|/rd/}} || {{Tengwar|j}} || {{IPA|/l/}} || {{Tengwar|m}} || {{IPA|/ld/}}
|-
|8 || {{Tengwar|8}} || {{IPA|/s/}} || {{Tengwar|i}} || {{IPA|/s/}} || {{Tengwar|k}} || Ss<br/>{{IPA|/sː/}} || {{Tengwar|,}} || Ss<br/>{{IPA|/sː/}}
|-
|9 || {{Tengwar|9}} || Hy<br/>{{IPA|/ç/}} || {{Tengwar|½}} || {{IPA|/h/}} || {{Tengwar|l}} || {{IPA|/j/}} || {{Tengwar|.}} || {{IPA|/w/}}
|}

{{Tengwar|3}} is an archaic consonant and need not be used. {{Tengwar|8}} and {{Tengwar|i}} represent the same sound, though {{Tengwar|i}} is preferred when a vowel is being written over top (see below). The same is true of {{Tengwar|k}} and {{Tengwar|,}}. 

==Vowels==
In order for a writing system to be considered a true alphabet, vowels and consonants must be treated equally. As this is not true of Tengwar, the system is technically an [[w:abugida|abugida]]. Vowels are, therefore, written '''above''' or '''below''' the consonant that comes before it.

===Short Vowels===
The five short vowels are written above the consonant.
*'''a''' = {{tengwar|1E `C}}
*'''e''' = {{tengwar|1R `V}}
*'''i''' = {{tengwar|1T `B}}
*'''o''' = {{tengwar|1Y `N}}
*'''u''' = {{tengwar|1U `M}}

{{Tengwar|1}} is being used as an arbitrary example to show that the vowels are written above the consonant. The second example, {{Tengwar|`}}, is a vowel carrier. This consonant is silent (and therefore not really a consonant) and only serves as a place holder for vowels when there is no consonant to write them over, like when it's at the beginning of a word.

===Long Vowels===
The five long vowels are written above a long vowel carrier, not a consonant.
*'''á''' = {{tengwar|~C}}
*'''é''' = {{tengwar|~V}}
*'''í''' = {{tengwar|~B}}
*'''ó''' = {{tengwar|~N}}
*'''ú''' = {{tengwar|~M}}

The carrier descends below the line (like the letters h, p, and q do in English), as to distinguish it from a short carrier.

===Diphthongs===
These are written differently than the other two types, mainly because the vowel is written above the consonant that comes '''after''' the vowel (which is the opposite of the usual). In the case of diphthongs, however, the consonant is actually the second vowel in the diphthong.

If you find this confusing, just ignore the above paragraph and memorize the forms without questioning why they break the typical vowel rules.

*'''ai''' = {{Tengwar|lE}}
*'''oi''' = {{Tengwar|lY}}
*'''ui''' = {{Tengwar|lU}}
*'''ei''' = {{Tengwar|lG}}
*'''au''' = {{Tengwar|.E}}
*'''eu''' = {{Tengwar|.T}}
*'''iu''' = {{Tengwar|.R}}

==Modifiers==
A number of strokes can be added to the tengwar to change their sound.

;Long consonants:The long consonants '''cc, ll, mm, nn, pp, rr''', and '''tt''' are denoted by adding a curved stroke below the "baseline" of the symbol. For example, {{Tengwar|1; t: j°}}.

;Palatalized consonants:These are simply consonants followed by the letter Y. This is written with two dots below the symbol (or inside, for the letter {{Tengwar|j}}. For example, {{Tengwar|1Î tÌ j´}}.

;Following S:A consonant followed by the letter S, such as ''ts, ps'', and ''ks'' (x), can be denoted by a downward hook to the "bow" (curved part) of the symbol. For example, {{Tengwar|1+ r+ z<nowiki>|</nowiki>}}.

==Punctuation==
*Period = {{Tengwar|-}}
*Semicolon = {{Tengwar|<nowiki>=</nowiki>}}
*Exclamation Point = {{Tengwar|Á}}
*Question Mark = {{Tengwar|À}}
*Parentheses = {{Tengwar|›}}

There is no separate parenthesis for the beginning or end of the enclosure.
